<Base title="Common Symptoms & Conditions">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>Common Symptoms and Conditions</h1>

    <p>
      Neuroplastic pain doesn't look the same for everyone, but there are patterns. If you recognize 
      several of these, it's worth exploring whether central sensitization is part of your picture.
    </p>

    <h2>The Three Hallmarks</h2>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0;">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">Hyperalgesia</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Things that should hurt a little hurt a LOT. A mild bump feels severe. Your pain volume knob is cranked up.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0;">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">Allodynia</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Things that shouldn't hurt at all now cause pain. A gentle touch, the pressure of clothing, a hug — these trigger pain.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0;">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">Sensory Hypersensitivity</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Bright lights, loud noises, strong smells, busy environments — they feel overwhelming or even painful.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Other Common Symptoms</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Widespread pain</strong> — pain in multiple areas that shifts location</li>
      <li><strong>Fatigue</strong> — deep, unrefreshing tiredness</li>
      <li><strong>Sleep problems</strong> — difficulty falling or staying asleep</li>
      <li><strong>Brain fog</strong> — trouble concentrating or remembering</li>
      <li><strong>Stress sensitivity</strong> — pain spikes during or after stress</li>
      <li><strong>Weather sensitivity</strong> — pain changes with weather pressure</li>
      <li><strong>Exercise intolerance</strong> — activity triggers flare-ups that last days</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conditions Linked to Central Sensitization</h2>
    <p>These conditions share the same underlying mechanism and often co-occur:</p>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
      <div class="card"><strong>Fibromyalgia</strong><br />Widespread pain, fatigue, sleep issues</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Chronic back/neck pain</strong><br />Pain persisting beyond tissue healing</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Migraine</strong><br />Frequent or chronic headaches</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>IBS</strong><br />Gut pain, bloating, altered bowel habits</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>TMJ disorder</strong><br />Jaw pain, clicking, tension</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Chronic pelvic pain</strong><br />Pelvic pain without clear structural cause</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Restless leg syndrome</strong><br />Uncomfortable urge to move legs</div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Interstitial cystitis</strong><br />Bladder pain and urgency</div>
    </div>

    <h2>When to consider neuroplastic pain</h2>
    <p>
      A strong clue is if you have <strong>multiple conditions</strong> from the list above, or if 
      <strong>tests come back normal</strong> despite persistent pain, or if <strong>treatments targeting 
      the body</strong> (surgery, injections, physical therapy) haven't helped or made things worse.
    </p>

    <div style="margin-top: 2rem; display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <a href="/intro/science" class="btn btn-primary">Next: The Science →</a>
      <a href="/quiz" class="btn btn-outline">Take the self-assessment quiz</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
